text: I NOW wish I hadn't seen the trailer, because it is probably the entire movie in one sitting.  This is why I get pissed off with modern Hollywood: they don't understand how to properly advertise for a new film....you should only show teases of what you'll see, not the whole feature....esp not if all the good parts come up and are used in the trailer.   Trailers used to hold you off on the good stuff, go for roughly 45 seconds or so, and only tell you what you need to know...now, we've got trailers over 2 minutes long explaining the entire premise and what is likely to happen by the end of the film.  For instance in this trailer, the information on the virus was completely unnecessary. Knowing it now, and seeing the rest to follow, I probably won't even want to see this film now....simply because the stupid trailer ruined a huge plot focus/twist, and possibly something crucial that would have caught me off guard.  Why do you always do this now, Hollywood....WHY? Is cuz cash grab? *Yehhh....probably for da cash grabz....*

It is like they shifted into fifth or sixth gear and did not know how to hit  a brake. Performances in the film are mostly fine and actors try their best, but they are constantly bogged down by lousy script and underwhelming character arcs that you just do not care. It is also one of those films that constantly need to explain everything, but when you as an audience member try to connect the spots you realize things just do not make any sense. Very disappointing. 2/5.

text: Leave it to modern cinema to make a villain spend his knowledge, money and his life invested in the end of the world in a way so it can be prevented by a child (or anyone for that matter), when it makes no sense for him to do that. A guy that was so determined of reducing the world population with a plague that he actually commits suicide, leaves a bunch of clues for his GF and the people that wanna prevent it, so they can wrestle in the pools of Istanbul? Seriously??? I presume the producer thought it was nice touch of faith or something... Imagine a murderer that wants to get caught. Thats right, you imagined lame movie plot only Hollywood can think of. This movie is one of those. Everything is wrong about it. The plot, the acting, the begging, the ending, the logic, the characters... Now I am led to believe that the book is also lame. The only people that enjoyed it, I figure, are the followers of Alex Jones and David Icke. Cheap. Glad I use torrents.

text: Of the three (3) films based on Dan Brown's books, The DaVinci Code (2006), Angels and Demons (2009) Inferno (2016) all directed by Ron Howard...This by far the weakest entry. This film leads me to question several issues; 1.) Is Tom Hanks getting too old to portray Robert Langdon?Â  2.) Is Ron Howard slipping as a film director and 3.) Has the Dan Brown mystique worn off?Â Â  Easily The Davinci Code scored $77M on opening weekend in 2006. Angels & Demons dropped down to $46M opening weekend in 2009 and Inferno dropped to $15M in 2016...undoubtedly executive at Sony are questioning the viability and future of the franchise. Tom Hank's acting ability is sustainable but,Â Robert LangdonÂ is a much younger man Hank's 60 years. Ron Howard's films have always paid attention to the overall story line with a focused attention to historical detail, clearly exhibited in both The Davinci Code and Angels & Demons, Inferno failed in both areas. In my opinion, unless there is a stronger commitment to reshape the DanÂ Brown books-to-film franchise...its not worth pursuing in the future.

text: After reading these lines from Dan Brown's 2009 interview (source wiki)...one thing I have understood. He is either a brainless man or the biggest liar ever born among humans. The Bible never gave a timeline to the creation of universe. The very first verse says...."In the beginning God created the heavens and the earth". The account of the creation of living beings is of 6 days. Only a fool will get the simple words wrong or intentionally twist them for self gain and fame. But the even bigger liar was that minister who didn't answer his question (if Dan is telling the truth in which case he is brainless).  "I was raised Episcopalian, and I was very religious as a kid. Then, in eighth or ninth grade, I studied astronomy, cosmology, and the origins of the universe. I remember saying to a minister, 'I don't get it. I read a book that said there was an explosion known as the Big Bang, but here it says God created heaven and Earth and the animals in seven days. Which is right?' Unfortunately, the response I got was, 'Nice boys don't ask that question.' A light went off, and I said, 'The Bible doesn't make sense. Science makes much more sense to me.' And I just gravitated away from religion. - Dan Brown

text: Is anyone else sick of weak movies trying to use other movies as crutches? Between the "wipe out half of the world" line here and the apocalyptic dream sequences, it seems that lazy film creation just involves blatant stealing from superhero movies.  It is also afraid of the mystery; Detective Pikachu could possibly have a better pay-off to the amnesia story-line and the lack of guts to stick with the downer ending is ridiculous. Also, teh bloody doorway looks like a "The Shining" spoof. Also, the "villain" was basically a human Thanos. The one thing which they should have ripped off from MARVEL, or better yet, kept from the book is gone. Also; Dan Brown's writing is far from perfect and the credibility of the "facts" there is average at best and immersion breaking or rage-inducing at worst. Still, they are worth reading at least once because he does know how to create an interesting narrative. This movie on the other hand looks like a sloppily made spin-off of Mission Impossible with Tom Hanks as Ethan Hunt. Like The last Jedi, Alien Covenant or Assassin's Creed:Odyssey, this movie does EVERYTHING to be a franchise killer.
